# NIJ Recidivism Forecasting — ML + Algorithmic Fairness Pipeline

> **NIJ 2021 Recidivism Forecasting Challenge** | Georgia parole cohort (2013–2015) | 25,835 individuals

A full ML pipeline for 3-year recidivism prediction with rigorous algorithmic fairness auditing, bias mitigation, and SHAP-based proxy detection. Built on the real NIJ 2021 challenge dataset, this project goes beyond prediction accuracy to formally quantify and mitigate disparate impact across race, gender, and intersectional subgroups.

---

## Key Findings

| Finding | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Gender > Race** | Gender gap (10.5-pp) is the primary fairness driver — not race (2.8-pp). Opposite of COMPAS-style analyses. |
| **Y2 Racial Gap Reverses** | WHITE has *higher* unconditional Year 2 recidivism (18.4% vs 17.7%) due to survivorship effects. |
| **NIJFM Design Flaw** | Predicting all-zeros nearly optimises the official NIJ fairness metric — a documented metric vulnerability. |
| **Informative Missingness** | `Gang_Affiliated` is missing in a race-dependent pattern (65.8% WHITE) — not missing-at-random. |
| **Proxy Channels** | `Supervision_Risk_Score_First` and `Residence_PUMA_*` are the primary SHAP channels encoding race. |

